1. Pipper auritum morphometrics analyses:

1.1. Loading data, standarization (normalization) of variables and merge with metadata

## 1. Loading database and filtering
    # Loading data
    # filtering: keep only "condimento" & "medicinal"
    # Change "CATEGORIAS" as factor and rename levels to: Culinario  & Medicinal
    morfometrics <- read.csv('./data/morfometrics-database.csv', stringsAsFactors = F) %>% 
        mutate(SampleID = paste("Sample", 1:nrow(.), sep = "_")) %>% 
        tibble::column_to_rownames(var = "SampleID") %>% 
        filter(CATEGORIAS %in% c("MEDICINAL", "CONDIMENTO")) #%>% 
    # rename(Dureza = DUREZA, Rendimiento = RENDIMIENTO); str(morfometrics)
    
## 2. Create metadata dataframe
    metadata <-  morfometrics %>% 
        tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "SampleID") %>% 
        select(1:5); str(metadata)

## 2. Extracting the coordinates of response variables (morfometrics) from the PCA
    responsevar <- data.frame(morfo.pca$var$coord, check.names = F) %>% 
        tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "ResponseVar")
    head(responsevar)
## 2. Extracting the individual (samples) coordinates
    ## Merge with with their metadata to later plot
    ## Change upper to lower case in the factor levels: "sitio" and "categorias"
    ## plotting the PCA using both: individuals (samples) and variables (resonse vars)
    
    data.frame (morfo.pca$ind$coord, check.names = F) %>% 
        tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "SampleID") %>% 
        inner_join(x = metadata, by = "SampleID") %>% 
        mutate(CATEGORIAS = factor(CATEGORIAS, levels = c("CONDIMENTO", "MEDICINAL"),
                     labels = c("Culinario", "Medicinal"))) %>% 
        mutate(SITIO = factor(SITIO, levels = c("HUERTO", "RUDERAL"),
                       labels = c("Huerto", "Ruderal"))) %>% 
        ggplot() +
        labs (x = paste ("PC1: ", paste(round (morfo.pca$eig[1,2], digits = 2), "%", sep = "")),
              y = paste ("PC2: ", paste(round (morfo.pca$eig[2,2], digits = 2), "%", sep = ""))) +
        ## adding data: samples coordinates points from the PCA
        geom_point(aes (x = Dim.1, y = Dim.2, shape = SITIO, colour = CATEGORIAS), 
               size = 5, alpha = 0.7) +
        # adding vectors as taxas
        geom_segment(data = responsevar,
                 aes(x = 0, y = 0, xend = Dim.1*3, yend = Dim.2*3),
                 arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.15, "cm")),
                 color = "black", show.legend = NA) +
        ## response variable names in front of each vectors: based on coordinates from the PCA
        ggrepel::geom_label_repel(data = responsevar, 
                      aes(x=Dim.1*4, y=Dim.2*4, label= ResponseVar),
                      segment.colour = NA, col = 'black', fill= "#FFFFFF", ##EEEEEE",
                      fontface = "italic",  box.padding = 0.6, size = 5) +
        stat_ellipse(aes(x=Dim.1, y=Dim.2, color = CATEGORIAS), type = "t") +
        scale_color_manual(name = "Categorías: ", values = c("firebrick3", "steelblue")) +
        scale_shape_manual(name = "Sitio", values=c(15,19)) +
        scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-4,4), breaks = seq(from = -4, to = 4, by = 2)) +
        scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-4,4), breaks = seq(from = -4, to = 4, by = 2)) +
        geom_hline(yintercept=0, linetype="dashed", color = "black") +
        geom_vline (xintercept = 0, linetype="dashed", color = "black") +
        theme_bw(base_size = 16) +
        theme(
            legend.position = "right",
            plot.margin = unit(c(0.5, 1.5, 0.4, 0.1), "cm"),
            legend.key=element_blank(), # background of guides-shapes are transparent
            legend.text = element_text(colour = "black", size = 16),
            ## lineas de los ejes X&Y:
            axis.line = element_line(size = 0.5, colour = "black", linetype = 1),
            # plot border and minor gridlines editing
            panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA, size = 0.4),
            panel.grid = element_blank(),
            # facet grid format:
            strip.text.x = element_text(size = 12, colour = "black", face = "bold"),
            ## axis titles font settings
            axis.title.y = element_text (color="black", size=15, vjust = 1, hjust = 0.5),
            axis.title.x = element_text (color="black", size=15,vjust = 1, hjust = 0.5),
            axis.text = element_text(color="black", size = 16),
            legend.title = element_text(color="black", size=14))

## perMANOVA: Using the filtered data

               data = morfo_std[,1:5], permutations = 9999, method = "euclidean",

2.1. Data loading: editing database

## 1. Loading database
    # Load the raw database of essential oils
    # change the firs colname
    # merge with their metadata
    # filter to keep "medicinal" & "condimento" levels
    # rename levels of CATEGORIAS to:
    data <- readxl::read_xlsx('./data/ACEITES_SITIOS.xlsx', sheet = 1)[,-30] %>% 
        dplyr::rename (TRATAMIENTO = SITIO) %>% 
        left_join(x = metadata, by = "TRATAMIENTO") %>% 
        filter(CATEGORIAS %in% c("MEDICINAL", "CONDIMENTO")) %>% 
        tibble::column_to_rownames(var = "SampleID") %>%

2.3. perMANOVA: essential oil content differences due to sites and categories based on permutational analysis of variance

Significantly differences in essential oil composition of Pipper auritum were observed among the sites where it was harvested (SITIOS, i.e., Ruderal versus Huerto) but not for the kind of usage, i.e., categories (uso medicinal versus uso culinario).

    ## perMANOVA: Using the filtered data
    # sink (file = './results/permanova-eoils.txt')
    vegan::adonis2 (formula = data[,5:ncol(data)] ~ SITIO * CATEGORIAS,
            data = data[,1:4], permutations = 9999, method = "euclidean",
            parallel = 4)
    # sink (file = NULL)

3. Barplot composition of the most abundant essential oils

Barplot with the 15 most abundant essential oil per site and cateogorie, in terms of relative abundace (total sum scaling, TSS, per sample).

## 1. define the colors: 15 colors (pals::alphabet2() palette)
    mycols <- c("#AA0DFE", "#3283FE", "#85660D", "#782AB6", "#565656", "#1C8356", "#16FF32", "#F7E1A0", "#E2E2E2", "#1CBE4F", "#C4451C", "#DEA0FD", "#FE00FA", "#325A9B", "#FEAF16")

## 2. Filter a dataframe with the top 15 essential oils (most abundat based on relative abundance)
    ## plot the stacked-%-barplot for the top 15 most abundant essential oil across samples
    data_top <- data %>%
        dplyr::select(-1:-5) %>% 
        t() %>% as.data.frame() %>%
        tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "oil_id")

    data_top %>%
        dplyr::arrange(desc(apply(X = data_top[,-1], MARGIN = 1, FUN = mean))) %>%
        head(., n = 15) %>%
        tibble::column_to_rownames(var = "oil_id") %>%
        t() %>%  as.data.frame() %>%
        tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "SampleID") %>%
        left_join(x = metadata, by = "SampleID") %>%
        pivot_longer(values_to = "relab", names_to = "essential_oil", cols = 6:20) %>%
        group_by(SITIO, CATEGORIAS, essential_oil) %>% 
        summarise(count = n(),
              avg = mean(relab),
              sd = sd(relab),
              sem = sd(relab)/sqrt(n())) %>% 
        magrittr::set_rownames(paste("Sample", 1:nrow(.), sep = "")) %>% 
        tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "SampleID") %>%
        as.data.frame() %>% 
        ggplot(aes (x = SITIO, y = avg, fill = essential_oil)) +
        geom_bar(position = "stack", stat = "identity") +
        scale_fill_manual(name = "Aceite esencial", values = mycols) + 
        theme_bw(base_size = 16) + 
        scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,50), breaks = seq(from = 0, to = 50, by = 10)) +
        labs (x = element_blank(), 
              y = "Abundancia relativa (%)\n",
              subtitle = "Top 15 most abundant essential oils across samples (n = 60)") +
        facet_grid(cols = vars(CATEGORIAS)) +
        theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, colour = "black"),
              axis.text = element_text(colour = "black", size = 16))
